{"title_page": "Yasushi Akimoto", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Yasushi Akimoto <br> {{nihongo2|\u79cb\u5143 \u5eb7}}\n| background          = non_performing_personnel\n| image               = Yasushi Akimoto.jpg\n| image_size          = 220px \n| alt                 =\n| caption             = Akimoto on 2012\n| birth_name          =\n| alias               =\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1958|5|2}}\n| birth_place         = [[Meguro, Tokyo]], Japan\n| origin              =\n| death_date          =\n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Japanese pop]]\n}}\n| occupation          = {{flatlist|\n* Record producer\n* lyricist\n* television writer}}\n| instrument          =\n| years_active        = 1973\u2013present{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}\n| label               = {{flatlist|\n* [[AKS Co., Ltd.|AKS]]\n* [[Fujisankei Communications Group#Fuji TV Group|Fuji-Pacific]]}}\n| associated_acts     = {{flatlist|\n* [[AKB48 Group]]\n* [[Sakamichi Series]]\n* [[22/7 (idol group)|22/7]]\n* [[Onyanko Club]]}}\n| website             =\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Yasushi Akimoto'''|\u79cb\u5143 \u5eb7|''Akimoto Yasushi''|born May 2, 1958|lead=yes}} is a Japanese [[record producer]], [[lyricist]], and television writer, best known for creating and producing some of Japan's top [[Japanese idol|idol]] groups, [[Onyanko Club]] and the [[AKB48]] franchise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://talent.yahoo.co.jp/pf/detail/pp157656|script-title=ja:\u79cb\u5143\u5eb7|accessdate=2015-11-11|publisher=Yahoo Japan Corporation|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.tokyo.jp/INET/KONDAN/2013/05/40n5o102.htm|script-title=ja:\u79cb\u5143\u5eb7\u6c0f\u30d7\u30ed\u30d5\u30a3\u30fc\u30eb|accessdate=2015-11-11|publisher=Tokyo Metropolitan Government|language=Japanese}}</ref> Total sales of the singles he has written exceed 100 million copies, making him the best-selling lyricist in Japan.<ref>{{cite web| script-title=ja:\u3010\u30aa\u30ea\u30b3\u30f3\u3011\u79cb\u5143\u5eb7\u6c0f\u3001\u4f5c\u8a5e\u30b7\u30f3\u30b0\u30eb\u7dcf\u58f2\u4e0a\u304c1\u5104\u679a\u7a81\u7834\u300c34\u5e74\u9593\u306e\u7a4d\u307f\u91cd\u306d\u300d| url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2063602/full/| work=[[Oricon]]| language=Japanese| date=2015-12-09| accessdate=2016-02-04}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAkimoto created the ''Chakushin Ari'' (''One Missed Call'') horror franchise, which began with his novel of the same name and was first brought to film in [[One Missed Call (2003 film)|2003]] before being [[One Missed Call (2008 film)|remade by Hollywood in 2008]]. He wrote both the novel and the screen adaptation for ''[[One Missed Call: Final]]''.\n{{expand section|date=January 2014|1=more details on how he started AKB48 and also all his activities prior to the 48 franchise, add when he expanded the franchise and where he learned how to write songs, also how he gets his inspirations}}\nAkimoto became a television writer in high school, he has produced many television programs, such as ''[[Utaban]]''.\n\nAkimoto started as a lyricist with [[The Alfee]] in 1981; he has written [[lyrics]] for various artists such as [[Kinki Kids]], [[Tunnels (owarai)|Tunnels]], [[Onyanko Club]], [[AKB48]], [[SKE48]], [[SDN48]], [[NMB48]], [[HKT48]], [[NGT48]], [[STU48]], [[Nogizaka46]] and [[Keyakizaka46]]. He also wrote [[Hibari Misora]]'s last single during her lifetime, \"[[Kawa no Nagare no Y\u014d ni]]\", and [[Jero]]'s debut single \"Umi Yuki\".\n\n<!--- commented out as the TPE48 project did not launch\nAkimoto is planning to launch a [[Taiwanese pop|Taiwan]] version of AKB48 in summer 2011. The group is temporarily named Taiwan48 or [[TPE48]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://asiapacificarts.usc.edu/article@apa?taiwan48_idol_group_to_launch_in_summer_16456.aspx | title = Taiwan48 idol group to launch in summer | publisher = Asia Pacific Arts | date = 03/01/2011}}</ref> In February, there were reports that TPE48 would debut summer of 2011, but there had been no further development since until this announcement. However there are plans to hold auditions for TPE48 in early 2012 and to debut as early as Summer 2012.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://asiapacificarts.usc.edu/article@apa?yasushi_akimoto_to_expand_the_akb48_franchise_overseas_to_indonesia_and_taiwan_17478.aspx | title = Yasushi Akimoto to expand the AKB48 franchise overseas to Indonesia and Taiwan | publisher = Asia Pacific Arts | date = 10/06/2011}}</ref>\n--->\nHe debuted the 1st international sister group of AKB48 called [[JKT48]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.populartrash.com/2012/02/22/akb-48-the-new-talent-model-originated-from-japan-and-beyond/ | title = AKB48 the new talent model from Japan and beyond | publisher = PopularTrash | date = 2012-02-24}}</ref> Auditions were held on October 8 and 9, 2011 and the official members were announced early November.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://asiapacificarts.usc.edu/article@apa?yasushi_akimoto_to_expand_the_akb48_franchise_overseas_to_indonesia_and_taiwan_17478.aspx | title = Yasushi Akimoto to expand the AKB48 franchise overseas to Indonesia and Taiwan | publisher = Asia Pacific Arts | date = 2011-10-06}}</ref> And the 2nd international sister group of AKB48 called [[SNH48]] was announced in October, 2012. On June, 2016 it was announced that SNH48 and its sister groups became fully independent from AKB48 having [[BEJ48]], [[GNZ48]], [[SHY48]] and [[CKG48]] as SNH48's Local Sister Groups which formed an alliance known as [[SNH48 Group]] or Star48. The 3rd international sister group of AKB48 called [[BNK48]] was announced on February 12, 2017. The 4th international sister group of AKB48 called [[TPE48]] was announced on February 4, 2018. And [[MNL48]] the 5th international sister group of AKB48, the 1st generation members were officially announced on April 28, 2018. Also on the same year, [[MUM48]], [[AKB48-China]] and [[SGO48]] were formed too as 6th, 7th and 8th overseas sister groups respectively.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nAkimoto also got involved in [[Joshi Puroresu|female professional wrestling]], introducing wrestler [[Cutie Suzuki]].<ref name=Files>{{cite book|author=|title=Pride: The Secret Files|url=|date=2008|publisher=Kamipro|isbn=|page=|language= Japanese}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007 he became a professor and vice president at [[Kyoto University of Art and Design]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kyoto-art.ac.jp/en/about/vpresident.html |title=A Message from the Vice President |accessdate=2010-10-06 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080615160414/http://www.kyoto-art.ac.jp/en/about/vpresident.html |archivedate=June 15, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, 2014 it was announced that Akimoto was named a member of the [[2020 Summer Olympics|2020 Tokyo Olympics]] Committee and was put in charge of producing the opening ceremony along with photographer [[Mika Ninagawa]] who has previously produced music videos for [[AKB48]], including 2010's [[Heavy Rotation (song)|Heavy Rotation]] and 2013's [[Sayonara Crawl]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2014-03-22/akb48-producer-akimoto-to-produce-2020-tokyo-olympics-opening-ceremony | title=AKB48 Akimito Yasushi to produce 2020 Olympics Opening Ceremony | publisher = Anime News Network  | date = 2014-03-23}}</ref> A petition against his appointment has been created due his representing the \"decline\" of the Japanese entertainment industry, with 11,000 signatures as of March 23.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2014-03-22/akb48-producer-akimoto-to-produce-2020-tokyo-olympics-opening-ceremony | title = AKB48 Akimito Yasushi to produce 2020 Olympics Opening Ceremony | publisher = Anime News Network | date = 2014-03-23}}</ref>\n\nHe also contributed in forming a South Korean girl group [[Iz*One]] with collaboration between AKS and Mnet.<ref>https://english.shukanbunshun.com/2017/11/produce-48-by-akb48-group-yasushi.html</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Japanese idol girl group multimedia project between Yasushi Akimoto, Aniplex, and Sony Music Records called [[22/7 (group)|22/7]] was formed. The project is described as \"idols who transcend dimensions.\" The members consist of voice actresses who provide the voice and motion capture for their characters, as well as perform as a musical group.\n\nIn 2019, Akimoto is no longer part of the [[AKS (company)|AKS]] management and is involved only as the creative producer of [[AKB48 Group]]s.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nikkansports.com/entertainment/akb48/news/201905060000085.html | script-title=ja:\u6307\u539f\u8389\u4e43\u3001\uff2e\uff27\uff34\u5c71\u53e3\u554f\u984c\u73fe\u72b6\u8a9e\u308b\u3000\u79cb\u5143\uff30\u306b\u76f8\u8ac7\u3082 | language=ja | work=[[Nikkan Sports]] | date=2019-05-06 | accessdate=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nAkimoto married [[Onyanko Club]] member [[Mamiko Takai]] in 1988.\n\n==Controversies==\nYasushi Akimoto's lyrics for AKB48 has been criticized for the perceived sexually-suggestive lyrics found in their song \"[[Seifuku ga Jama o Suru]]\". It addressed the issue of [[Enjo k\u014dsai]] from a first person view, and was considered by some Western reporters unsuitable for its young members. When asked about this by [[CNN]]'s [[Anna Coren]], he said that his lyrics \"depict[ed] reality\" and were meant to prompt the consideration of difficult issues.<ref name=\"cnnasiapacific20120112\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cnnasiapacific.com/press/en/content/757/ |title=JAPANESE IDOL GROUP AKB48 FOUNDER YASUSHI AKIMOTO ON CNN\u2019S TALK ASIA \u2013 Press Releases \u2013 Turner Asia |work=Turner International Asia Pacific |date=January 12, 2012 |accessdate=June 5, 2012 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121226172710/http://www.cnnasiapacific.com/press/en/content/757/ |archivedate=December 26, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"editioncnncom20120113\">{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1201/13/ta.01.html|title=CNN.com \u2013 Transcripts \u2013 TALK ASIA \u2013 Interview with Japanese Music Producer Yasushi Akimoto|date=January 13, 2012|accessdate=June 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* 2008: 41st [[Japan Lyricist Awards]] \u2014 Grand Prix (for the song \"Umiyuki\", performed by [[Jero]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jla-official.com/taisho/e_no_041.html|script-title=ja:\u7b2c41\u56de\u65e5\u672c\u4f5c\u8a69\u5927\u8cde|trans-title=The 41st Japan Lyricist Awards|accessdate=2015-05-07|publisher=Japan Lyricists Association|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n* 2009: 51st [[Japan Record Award]] Special Award<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/71224/full/|publisher=oricon ME inc.|language=Japanese|script-title=ja:\u300e\u7b2c51\u56de\u65e5\u672c\u30ec\u30b3\u30fc\u30c9\u5927\u8cde\u300f\u5019\u88dc11\u4f5c\u54c1\u6c7a\u5b9a \u6700\u512a\u79c0\u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0\u306fGReeeeN\u300e\u5869\u3001\u30b3\u30b7\u30e7\u30a6\u300f\u306b|accessdate=2015-11-11}}</ref>\n*2011: 16th The AMD Award  \u2014  Grand Prize <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amd.or.jp/award/16/works/01.html|title=\u7b2c16\u56deAMD Award '10 \u53d7\u8cde\u4f5c\u54c1\u4e00\u89a7 \uff0d AMD \u4e00\u822c\u793e\u56e3\u6cd5\u4eba\u30c7\u30b8\u30bf\u30eb\u30e1\u30c7\u30a3\u30a2\u5354\u4f1a|website=amd.or.jp|access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref>\n* 2012:  54th Japan Record Award \u2014  Lyricist Award. 45th Japan Cable Award, Special Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2018729/full/|title=2012\u5e74\u300e\u65e5\u672c\u6709\u7dda\u5927\u8cde\u300f\u306f\u6c37\u5ddd\u304d\u3088\u3057 2\u5e74\u3076\u308a\u53f2\u4e0a\u6700\u591a7\u56de\u76ee\u306e\u5927\u8cde|website=ORICON NEWS|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref>\n* 2017: 19th [[Mnet Asian Music Awards]] \u2014 Inspired Achievement\n\n==See also==\n* [[AKB48]]\n* [[Nurse Angel Ririka SOS]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.fujipacific.co.jp/artists/songwriters/akimotoyasushi.html Fujipacific Music Inc] 